description:
Affiliations are now due in respect of the 2013 Calendar Year. It is important that all those involved in Table Tennis - coaches, umpires, referees, administrators and players - are registered members of the ITTA.

Why are Affiliations necessary ?

  • As a source of income – which will support the development of our Sport through  ITTA events and initiatives, such as Women In Sport Coaching, the Schools Development Programme, Tournaments, Provincial and National Training Camps, Level 1/2 Coaching Courses and the Junior Participation Series.
  • In support of our Grant Application – the level of Affiliates is a key determinant in the allocation of our Core Grant as an NGB. Therefore, increased affiliations will generally result in a higher Grant Allocation, which in turn will increase your Association’s resources to develop our Sport.
  • As a source of information – the number and geographical location of our affiliate base provides the Association with valuable information, which is a key ingredient in developing strategies and initiatives to promote and develop our Sport throughout the country.
  • As a means of communication – for the delivery of Hotshots, Ezines, Tournament Entry Forms, and all relevant information from the TT world.

 What are the Benefits of Affiliation ?

  • Identify with your Sport – All sports players register with their National Governing Body. The ITTA is the NGB for Table Tennis in Ireland and is affiliated to the International Table Tennis Federation and the European Table Tennis Union.
  • Child Protection – all affiliates are protected by the ITTA’s Child Protection Policies and the Access NI (in NI) and Garda vetting procedures (in ROI) which conform to the highest standards. The Association has a dedicated Vetting Officer.
  • Sport Development - while ISC and Sport NI funding is the primary source of income, the Association depends on sponsorship, fundraising and affiliation fees to invest in your sport and support the activities and initiatives to promote the sport throughout the country. Your affiliation fees are supporting the development of your sport.
  • Tournaments – all affiliates are eligible to participate in all ITTA approved tournaments and events.
  • Participation – the ITTA supports a wide range of initiatives which foster the development of the Sport at Primary, Secondary and University levels.  Participation projects are guided by our part-time WIS Co-ordinator. Focus is on co-ordinating our Schools Development Programme and on the continued development of the successful STIGA Junior Challenger Series which encourages participation at all levels.
  • Coaching – the ITTA provides Coaching Ireland certified Coaching Courses for affiliated members, which are facilitated by the qualified Tutors in the country.
  • Training Camps – affiliated members can attend Provincial and National Training Camps if they are selected by their respective Provincial / National Coaches.
  • Opportunity to represent your Province/Country – all affiliates are eligible for Provincial and National Team selection, depending on specific selection criteria.
  • Awards – each year, the Association recognizes outstanding achievements and contributions to the Sport through the ITTA Annual Awards. All affiliates are eligible for these awards, which include Best Male/Female Coach, Best Male/Female/Junior Player, Volunteer and Press Officer of the Year.
  • TT Information – the ITTA is committed to communicating relevant and timely information on all TT related matters, such as previews and reviews of Domestic and International Competitions, Irish/Provincial Squads, Events and Initiatives, World TT News, Tournament Application Forms and Updates and Newsletters from our Sponsors. This is achieved through our new interactive Website, weekly and ad hoc Hotshots which are emailed to all affiliates, and our Event Marketing Stand.
  • Referees, Umpires and Regulations – the ITTA is responsible for regulating  the Sport of TT in Ireland, and ensuring that properly trained Referees and Umpires are available to ensure that the ITTF rules and regulations are strictly adhered to. Umpire courses are available to all affiliates.
  • Advice – the ITTA is always on hand through its full-time manager to answer all your queries related to TT matters.
  • Opportunities – to meet new friends and to enjoy your Sport!

 

The ITTA is the NGB for Your Sport.

It is committed to facilitating all players at all levels who want to develop to their potential, and enjoy the sport of Table Tennis.

 By Affiliating, you are supporting the Association’s efforts in developing your Sport.

 Table Tennis is a Sport for All, and your Sport for Life !

 If you require any further information on the ITTA or any Table Tennis related matter, or have any comments or suggestions, please log on to our Website (www.irishtabletennis.com) or contact our Manager, Mr Darren Coombes on 01-6251135 or by email on manager@irishtabletennis.com).

description:
Writers and filmmakers need to understand their legal rights and how to defend themselves from those who may seek to exploit them. Production companies and distributors often know all the tricks of the trade, while writers and filmmakers know little about how to protect themselves. This seminar, geared towards both artists and attorneys representing artists, explains how writers and filmmakers can prevent problems from arising by properly securing underlying rights, and by encouraging the other party to live up to agreements by adding performance milestones, default penalties and arbitration clauses. In the event of a dispute, participants learn what remedies are available to enforce their rights. Related topics include creative approvals, typical compensation and terms of studio contracts, merchandising deals, and negotiating tactics and strategies. The seminar includes more than 100 pages of useful contracts, checklists, forms and materials.

 

Mark Litwak is an entertainment attorney based in Beverly Hills, California. His practice includes work in the areas of copyright, trademark, contract, multimedia law, intellectual property, and book publishing. As a Producer’s Representative, he assists filmmakers in arranging financing, marketing and distribution of their films. Litwak is the author of six books:  Reel Power, The Struggle for Influence and Success in the New Hollywood (William Morrow, 1986), Courtroom Crusaders (William Morrow, 1989), Dealmaking in the Film & Television Industry (Silman-James Press, 1994) (winner of the 1996 Krasna-Krausz award for best book in the world on the film business), Contracts for the Film & Television Industry (Silman-James Press, 2nd Ed. 1999), Litwak's Multimedia Producer's Handbook (Silman-James Press, 1998) and  Risky Business: Financing and Distributing Independent Film  (Silman-James Press, 2004). He has contributed articles for The Los Angeles Times, The Business of Film, The Hollywood Reporter, Moviemaker and The Independent.  He is the creator of the popular CD-ROM program Movie Magic Contracts. Litwak has been a lawyer for 33 years. He has an AV Peer Review Rating from Martindale-Hubbell and has been named a Southern California Super Lawyer by Law & Politics magazine in 2006 and 2007. He also has served as an expert witness in movie industry disputes and is an IFTA Arbitrator.
name: Self Defense for Writers and Filmmakers: For Artists and Attorneys

monkeyface eel champion, blogger and street performer Kirk Lombard on an inter-
tidal fishing trip along the city’s bayfront shoreline. Learn the basics of how to “poke pole” for the

Discover the best local mussel beds, where to find stands of edible sea weeds, discuss
what’s running where and when and why. Learn what’s safe to eat and what’s not: why
forage fish are better than sexy game fish, why a surf smelt is better than a jack smelt,
why a kingfish shouldn’t be eaten in the summer, why the old wive’s tale about eating
shellfish in months that have “r’s” in them could lead to your early (and painful) death
by paralytic shellfish poisoning. Discuss how to catch and pickle herring (in season).
Also included, will be a short trip along the real Fisherman’s Wharf, (yes, in addition
to tee shirts, fish are actually bought and sold there) with a brief overview of our local
commercial fisheries: historically, what fish have been caught in our region? What is
being caught today? What is the relative sustainability of each local fishery? This tour
will require a bit of walking and patience. If you can’t make it up the hill between Fort

Top celebrity & editorial stylists Ilaria Urbinati, Soyon An and Karla Welch offer tips and tricks of the business to fashion’s next generation of tastemakers

 

Simply Stylist’s seasonal seminar will feature stylists Soyon An, Ilaria Urbinati and Karla Welch giving the next generation of fashion tastemakers the chance to learn from the best. On March 18th, An, Urbinati, and Welch will join guests at Hollywood’s Eden lounge, for a 3-part seminar and a Q&A session that will unlock the secrets of their profession to aspiring stylists and fashion lovers of all types.

 

Simply Stylist aims to give the next generation of fashion tastemakers a new opportunity to hear and learn from the best this season with featured speakers Illaria Urbinati, Soyon An and Karla Welch. Urbinati began her career at eighteen as a retail buyer, delivering fashion direct to consumers and eventually parlaying her innate sense of style and knowledge of fashion behind the scenes. Urbinati’s work has been featured in the pages of top US and international magazines, broadcast and print advertising as well as top Hollywood talent Emmy Rossum, Bradley Cooper, Ashley Greene, James McAvoy and others as well as owning her own freestanding retail space, Confederacy in Los Angeles. Two-Time Emmy Award® winning Costume Designer and Stylist Soyon An may be best known for her work on FOX’s American Idol and So You Think You Can Dance but her knowledge of the fashion industry extends far beyond. An began her career in fashion design and today implements her knowledge of garment construction to create dazzling looks for her clients which include tours for Carrie Underwood, appearances for Jennifer Lopez, Broadway play Dangerous Beauty and her on-going role as Editor for fashion magazine, Jimon. Karla Welch makes up the West Coast half of the styling team Karla and Kemal, together these powerhouse women bring the best of New York and Los Angeles to their work. Welch, who was raised in British Columbia, partnered with Kemal after a chance meeting during New York Fashion Week. Today, the duo’s work can be seen on red carpets and magazines across the globe on actresses like Olivia Wilde, America Ferrera, Zooey Deschanel, Feist, Hailee Steinfeld, Chloe Sevigny and Amy Poehler. 

 

For those interested in breaking into the industry, looking for fashion advice for their figure, or just wondering where on earth fashion is heading next, the Simply Stylist seminar is not to be missed. Guests will have an opportunity to hear the stories of working stylists and costume designers as well as get a chance to ask questions of these remarkable women. Guests of Simply Stylist’s seminar will also have an opportunity to be featured in a viral video on www.simplystylist.com discussing their take on fashion, designers and emerging looks.


STYLIST BIOS


ILARIA URBINATI

Ilaria Urbinati began her career at 18 as a retail buyer, before landing a job as Head Stylist forThe L Word. Since then, she has been freelance styling for magazines including Elle, GQ Italy, Flaunt, Nylon and InStyle.Ilaria has styled runway shows for the likes of Agent Provocateur, commercials for NBC, ABC, and Bravo, in addition to print advertising and catalog work. She has worked with celebrities including: Zooey Deschanel, Ashley Greene, Isla Fisher, Emma Stone, James McAvoy, Bradley Cooper, Emile Hirsch and Ben Foster.In 2008, Ilaria and Danny Masterson opened Confereracy in Los Feliz, a store catering to hipster locals and fashionable celebrities and musicians. Ilaria has a women’s line out with renowned designer Rebecca Minkoff and a line of suits with client Albert Hammond Jr. of The Strokes.


SOYON AN

Two time Emmy winner Soyon An may be best known for her work on FOX’s American Idol and So You Think You Can Dance, but her knowledge of the fashion industry extends far beyond. Soyon began her career in fashion design and today implements her knowledge of garment construction to create dazzling looks for her clients who include among others Carrie Underwood, Jennifer Lopez, Jordin Sparks, Kris Allen and Adam Lambert.  Her press coverage includes Glamour, People, WWD, Emmy magazine, OK magazines. As a stylist, Soyon has collaborated with Mariah Carey, Kate Bosworth, Mia Maestro and Avril Lavigne as well as other independent musicians. Soyon is fashion editor and creative director of the international, fashion forward, Jimon Magazine (www.jimon-magazine.com). She is also is currently designing the costumes for the Broadway play “Dangerous Beauty.”

                                                                       

KARLA WELCH

Karla Welch makes up the West Coast half of styling team Karla and Kemal. The duo uses their unique bi-coastal partnership to bring the best of both New York and Los Angeles fashion to their clients. Welch, who was raised in British Columbia, partnered with Kemal after a chance meeting during New York Fashion Week. Their forward thinking relationship keeps them on the current pulse of pop culture and is quickly turning them into industry favorites. Their editorial work has been featured in Nylon, Lula, Rolling Stone, and Interview. They have worked with celebrity clients like Olivia Wilde, America Ferrera, Zooey Deschanel, Feist, Amy Poehler, advertising clients such as MTV, Apple, Dooney & Bourke, and Holt Renfrew, and they are currently collaborating with Kwiat jewelers on projects for awards season and have also created a “K+K” handbag for Hong Kong-based line Mata Hari’s stylist collection to be released in Fall 2010.

We Players final 2011 Alcatraz exhibit, "Images from Inside" runs August 27- November 30, 2011. 



The National Park Service and We Players have invited the Prison Arts Project, which sponsors on-going art classes at San Quentin through the William James Association, to exhibit outstanding examples of its work in "Images from Inside."  The exhibit will also include visual art from the former California Arts-in-Corrections program - now collected by UCLA Library's Prison Arts Archiving Project and WJA. This exhibit is the most comprehensive gathering of inmate-produced artwork in the Bay Area in many years.


The August 27th exhibition-opening event will include a panel discussion representing the largest gathering of minds in prison arts programming in the Bay Area in over a decade. Panelists include:

            Larry Brewster, Professor, USF

            Laurie Brooks, Executive Director, William James Association

            Steve Emerick, former Arts-in-Corrections Artist/Facilitator; recipient of Dalai

                     Lama’s Compassion Award

            Patrick Maloney, San Quentin art teacher for 23 years

            Katya McCulloch, San Quentin art teacher for 6 years

            Carol Newborg, Exhibit Organizer for WJA, former AIC teacher

Panel moderated by: Patrick Gillespie, We Players Gallery Curator

 

(Image Credit: Artist Studio Self-Portrait Collaboration, Cyanotype print series. Arts-in-Corrections, 1987.)

 

Images on the Inside - Exhibition Information

The successful collaboration of the public and the inmate population is one of the foundations of Arts-in-Corrections, which existed from 1980-2010 in the California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation. That model was started in 1977 by the initial Prison Arts Project, which used professional artists, writers, and performers as teachers and role models of discipline, skill and commitment to growth and hard work.

 

Participation in Arts-in-Corrections correlates to a lower recidivism rate, thus significantly reducing costs for the state and helping people to stay out of prison upon their release. A university study found that participants in the AIC program had a 27% lower recidivism rate than the general prison population. Ninety percent of inmates will return to life outside the prison walls, and arts and educational programming helps address the challenges of re-entry through public collaboration and creative growth. (click here for links to study)

 

This exhibition was curated by Carol Newborg of the William James Association and Patrick Gillespie, We Players Gallery Curator.  

 

We Players on Alcatraz

In 2009, the National Park Service invited We Players to engage in a monumental collaboration on Alcatraz Island. This groundbreaking partnership has utilized site-specific performing arts, and local outreach and education programming to provoke critical thought and stimulate conversation on the Alcatraz themes of incarceration, isolation, justice and redemption. In culmination of this three-year residency, We Players has organized a series of art exhibits for a gallery in the Alcatraz Cell House. Images on the Inside is the final exhibit in the 2011 series.

As we emerge from a volatile financial market environment, now - more than ever - is the time to convene to examine fresh ideas, build trusted networks, and participate in substantive, in-depth conversations about how to raise funds, generate deals, manage the portfolio, and realize exits. So with this in mind, a group of motivated women in Huntsville Alabama  are organizing  Tennessee Valley's  Women in Business  luncheon on June 25, 2011 featuring  A'Lelia Bundles, the great great granddaughter of the late Madam C.J. Walker as the keynote speaker and would be honored to have you as one of  our guest for this spectacular event.

The mission of the Women in Business  luncheon  is to bring together an influential and powerful inner circle to facilitate sharing of hard-to-get information; encourage women to widen their network and do business with each other; and increase their access to information that will inspire and empower them so that they can advance professionally, develop personally, and provide leadership in their communities, the nation, and the world. 

We are proud to be a part of this Women in Business  movement  to release the fears about what we can achieve  and live out the truest expression of ourselves as human beings as we step on to grand stage of our own lives. Food, fun, and fashion all for a good cause are what makes up the Nellie's Catwalk for Kids (NC4K) fashion show. Join Nellie along with 300 local models as they take the stage to stand up against childhood cancer on Friday August 5th at Ohio Dominican University. The fashion show is being dedicated to three children, Faith Pruden, Sam Bish, and Violet Baier, that lost their battle to childhood cancer this past year.

The fashion show is made up of five entertaining scenes that will go back in time, starting with the roaring twenties, all the way up to today's trends.

The pre-party starts outside Ohio Dominican University at 6:00PM. The pre-party is for all fashion show guests and will include free food from local restaurants, a live local band, photobooth, silent auction, cash bar, and the Nellie's shop filled with NC4K merchandise, trendy accessories, and booths of the presenting sponsors. The fashion show portion will begin at 7:00PM with emcees that are the Nellie's News anchors, which are directily touched by childhood cancer. Tickets to attend are $20.00 in advance and $25.00 at the door.

The NC4K fashion show is presented by Olentangy Pediatrics, Key Bank, Round 2, Miche Bag, and Knights of Columbus.

To purchase tickets, make a donation, or to find out more information log onto www.catwalk4kids.com and to find Nellie's fan page on Facebook search for Nellie's Catwalk for Kids.

 

 

Background Information:

Nellie's Catwalk for Kids (NC4K) was started back in 2006 by Nellie Krumlauf when she was 16 years old in the efforts of bringing childhood cancer to the forefront. The organization started off as just a summer fashion show wanting to get local kids and teens involved in helping make a magical difference. NC4K has now evolved to a 501 C3 non-profit that has four main community events a year including: a dance marathon, 5K run, golf outing, and the fashion show. In addition to community events NC4K has over 15 high school Nellie's Clubs all ran by upperclassmen. The first Nellie's Club was started back in 2009 by Jessica Soroky at Pickerington North High School; she is now the manager of all of the clubs and helping NC4K expand to other high schools. NC4K's mission is to actively help kids and teens and their families that are touched by cancer. The money raised from all of our events help us work in conjunction with Nationwide Children's Hospital Oncology Unit by supporting the families in every way possible. Funds raise also help us raise more awareness for pediatric cancer and grow the organization as a whole. NC4K's main goals are to inform communities of how they can help pediatric cancer families, to raise more funds for families with a child battling cancer, to empower kids, teens and young adults to make a difference, to eventually expand outside of Ohio to help other families, and the ultimate goal of helping find a cure!

 

Ways to get involved:

NC4K has many easy and fun ways to give back. The most popular way is to become a summer fashion show model, along with starting a Nellie's Club at a high school to raise funds and awareness for NC4K. Other involvement opportunities include: volunteering at events, financial support, making fleece blankets for patients, collecting pop tabs for the hospital, hosting a fundraiser to benefit NC4K, and simply spreading the word.

ASPIRE (Asian Sisters Participating in Reaching Excellence) is a Boston-based non-profit organization dedicated to Asian American girls and women in the area of career and leadership development. With a strong membership base of 500+ members nationwide and 150+ professional volunteers, we develop programs that engage, educate and empower Asian American high school, college, and professional women to become effective, lifelong leaders.

The Asian American (AA) community often faces stereotypes of being a “model minority”– an ethnic group that has already achieved success and needs little support. As a result, AA girls often lack mentors and role models. AA girls that struggle to fulfill the “model minority” myth are at severe risk for mental illness, challenged by the clash between American individualism and the Asian tradition of putting family and community first. ASPIRE aims to empower AA women through customized leadership training and career development, hands-on civic engagement in their communities and schools, and individual mentoring. Our goal is to improve their coping skills, self-confidence, mental and career outlook.

Men's Tinderbox, 27th Sept 7-9pm

and

Women's Tinderbox, 28th Sept 7-9pm

 

Our next Tinderbox events, one for women, one for men, will be held in Marylebone, from 7-9pm. Please register to come and we'll then send you further joining details. Both events are free, but we warmly welcome donations towards the venue hire and further work of Women on Fire. Thank you.

________

Helping women to become really effective decision makers includes their personal lives. This is often a matter of confidence and clout, both boosted by joining forces with other women.

Where decisions are generally led by men and affect large chunks of society, engaging men in strenghtening their receptivity (the feminine principle) and the ability to listen without prejudice, works towards a true collaboration.

Hence at the moment two different approaches and two separate TINDERBOX meetings. Please remember that the practices introduced at TINDERBOX are unusual. For some they're unusually powerful. Even if you think this is all very odd, there'll be something in it for you.

You don't need to understand the language of TINDERBOX. It doesn't matter if your intellectual self dismisses or draws you back from reading this. Your body (without which your mind is after all somewhat adrift) needs the resources of the earth, the energy of the sun and the fire at the earth's core which helps to make our atmosphere. Engaging with those fundamentals, including gravity helps to make you feel at home in yourself, as yourself. And to feel a valued part of something.

Come for an adventure. It will be entirely pleasurable unless you want your existing criteria to define where you are going, or even more discomforting, are certain that you already know and want to be seen as a knower. Think childhood. Think unselfconscious happy discovery. There are untapped resources in each of us, often bundled up, judged and made unavailable by reason. We properly value our capacity for logic and clear-thinking. That part often gets the casting vote. But there's also a wise, instinctual self every bit as useful. This is a less subjective resource, an 'inner tuition' accessed through awareness of what governs our bodies and makes us all equal. It's therefore inclusive, not only of other people but of other forms of life.

Come to TINDERBOX to connect with the fire in the earth and in you. Come to experience a deeper rootedness, and the peace that arises. Come to contribute to the power of joined-up fire - the shared current flowing hip to hip in women, shoulder to shoulder in men.

Each Meeting

Each meeting will begin promptly at 7pm, and will begin with a short introduction. Then we'll move directly to the practice to connect individually and then collectively to core fire. THis is  so that any discussion comes from a shared experience of a great resource, and is the foundation for subsequent periods of silence and listening with alert stillness. 

After this there'll be a chance to meet others and speak one to one until the close of TINDERBOX at 9pm.

Check out the film clips of the practice and the one minute silence (we've shortened it!) from our inaugural event at http://womenonfire.co.uk/pg/pages/view/397/video

Registration

Please reserve a seat by registering above. Then we'll email you details of the venue and some local cafes where you can carry on networking after 9pm. Please respect the place that you have put your name to. If you've researved a seat and then can't come, please let us know so that we can reallocate your place to someone else. Thanks,

Because of the format, it's vital that you are there on time. Latecomers will not be admitted.

8:30am-12:30pm @ MIT Media Lab

Are you interested in helping your students:

  • imagine new possibilities of what they can do with computers?
  • learn to express themselves creatively with new technologies?

As students create and share Scratch projects, they learn to think creatively, reason systematically, and work collaboratively -- and develop as computational thinkers and computational creators.

This event is open to all Boston-area educators who have no prior Scratch experience. During this workshop, we will:

  • experience Scratch through demonstrations and hands-on activities

Competition Law and Policy in the Healthcare Sector: A Trans-Atlantic Perspective

Keynote speech by Prof. Fiona Scott Morton, Deputy Assistant Attorney General, US Department of Justice


Tuesday 6 December 2011 from 11.30 - 13:30pm
at UCL Faculty of Laws' Bloomsbury Campus

Organised by UCL's Centre for Law, Economics & Society


About the conference
Much healthcare provision is accomplished through networks of providers such as physicians, hospitals, pharmacies, and dentists. Common contract terms between the party organizing the network and the set of providers include non-discrimination terms like MFNs and network participation requirements. The talk will discuss theories of competitive effect and consumer harm resulting from such provisions, and cover empirical evidence of their impact in the healthcare sector.


This event is accredited with 1.5 CPD hours by the Solicitors Regulation Authority, Bar Standard Board and IPReg.

"One of those 'Once in a lifetime'

opportunities you can't miss."

 

'What a way to experience everything that makes Florida the most desirable vacation destination in America! Ride a beautiful, gentle horse along a sandy Florida beach lined with palm-trees. Soon, you'll make your way deeper into the warm waters of Palma Sola Bay to learn the secrets of horse-surfing and horse-skiing! Horseback riding on the beach is the ultimate vacation treat that won't soon be forgotten!

 

 

 

 


FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS

I don't see a beach ride scheduled on the day/time when I want to ride. Should I schedule a Private Ride? This popular and unique riding experience sells out fast, and once an event sells out we take it off the website. The dates and times you see are what we have available. All times are based on low-tide.

Who can participate in the beach experience?  Almost anyone can do this because we can adjust the ride depending on your experience level. We make it wicked fun for Barneys and expert riders alike. We accept children as young as 3. We welcome the disabled. Our only restriction is that you must weight under 220 lbs. Sorry, no exceptions.


I know how to ride, do I have to have a guide? If you can ride like a Comanche we'll let you ride on the beach without a guide, but everyone has a guide in the water. Sweet!

Will I ride bareback?  Yes, but not like that! We use bareback pads which are more comfy than sitting directly on the horse (but no stirrups). English and western-style saddles are available, but cannot be taken into the salt water. 

Can you accommodate more than 4 riders?  Yes, but not at the same time.  If you have 8-15 riders in your party, we can organize a weapons-grade beach party for you. Call 941-907-7272 for details.

Can Junior ride with an adult? Yes. But there are restrictions. The adult must be an accomplished rider with years of riding instructions. The combined weight of the adult and child must be under 200 lbs. The child must hold a ticket. No free lunch, baby!

Are Photographs and Videos permitted?  Professional-quality still images and videos are available above. You are also welcome to take your own photographs and/or bring your own photographer; however, there's an extra fee if your photographs are for commercial purposes.

Are spectators allowed? Spectators are always welcome. There is a public sidewalk parallel to the beach. The beach is open to the public.

Are dogs allowed? Yes! Palma Sola Bay is a pooch-friendly beach.
Horse Surfing - If you weigh less than 150 lbs and wish to try standing up on your horse (totally optional), your guide will teach you how to hang ten like a local for no extra charge. Horse Surfing was invented right here at Palma Sola Bay in Bradenton, FL! (see video below)


Refunds - All tickets are non-refundable. Please don't hate us.

Ticket Availability - To control quality and safety, we only sell 4 tickets for each event. If you have 8-15+ people in your group, we can throw a bitchin' beach party. Just give us a call at 941-907-7272.

Directions - We ride at Palma Sola Bay. There isn't an official address but the map coordinates are 27º 29' 46.24" N 82º 38' 43.25" W. We're right on Manatee Avenue, about 4 miles east of Homes Beach and 11 miles west of I-75. You'll be looking for a truck and horse trailer.

Do I need to print my tickets? Nah, just make sure you know when/where to go.


Rain/Cold - We reserve the right to delay/postpone/cancel your ride due to crappy weather or for any other rieason. If we are forced to cancel your ride due to weather or for any other reason, we will give you a rain check that can be used up to one year later. After that they start to get moldy.  You must be present and ready to ride at your scheduled time of departure to be eligible for a rain check.

What timeshould I be there? Plan to check-in about 15 minutes before your ride to sign release forms, ask questions, and get aquainted witour horses and staff. Please don't be late for your ride. Your ticket is only good for the times stated on your ticket. Your ride will end at the scheduled time reguardless of your arrival time.

How much should I tip? - Excellent question. If you're a cheap-skate or you have a really lousy time, $0-5 per person. If you're a working stiff or student like us, then $10-20 per person is average. If you have a truly awesome experience, then $25-50 per person is normal. If you flew into SRQ on a Gulfstream G550, then $100 each is very cool. All tips, no matter how small, are greatly appreciated.

Join Outdoor Photography Canada Magazine contributing editor and professional photographer, Paul Burwell, for a many-faceted workshop that will immerse you into the world of macro photography. We’ll spend the entire weekend together helping you learn about the aspects of macro photography necessary to produce compelling and well composed images. We’ll discuss the equipment the pros use, technical skills necessary to produce captivating images, learning to find macro photography opportunities, developing a creative vision to separate your photos from the average, choosing the right digital darkroom tools and techniques for selling your images.

This intensive weekend course isn't just about you listening to an instructor drone on and on, its about you getting an opportunity to try out some of the techniques discussed using your own digital camera with macro capabilities or a camera with a macro lens.  Paul will be with you every step of the way to help you come away with the best possible images.

Macro photography image of a snowflake

About your instructor for the Edmonton Macro Photography Class

Paul Burwell is a professional outdoor photographer, writer and educator. His images have appeared in numerous magazines, greeting cards, advertisements and calendars. He is a contributing editor for Outdoor Photography Canada Magazine where he has a regular column called “Let’s Go Digital!” In addition to the wildlife photography workshops and tours he hosts worldwide each year, he also teaches a number of photography classes at Edmonton’s Metro Community College. Paul has been a finalist in both the 2009 and 2010 Worldwide Veolia Wildlife Photographer of the Year competition and has been named by Popular Photography magazine as a “top shooter” of wildlife photography in their March 2010 issue featuring a two-page spread of Paul’s photo of a Snow Leopard.

Paul facilitates his workshops and tours in a cooperative and constructive environment and does not photograph for his own portfolio when he’s teaching. He is strictly there to help you learn.

Equipment Required for the Edmonton Macro Photography Class

To get the most out of this workshop, you DO NOT require the latest and greatest digital SLR camera with a monster telephoto lens. However, there are a few pieces of equipment that you’ll require to help maximize your experience.

 At a minimum, you’ll want to have…

  •  A digital camera manufactured in the last 5 years with macro photography capabilities
  • or a digital SLR camera with a macro photography lens
  • a tripod capable of supporting your camera and lens
  • a shutter release cable or wireless shutter release
  • Memory card(s) that can hold 200-300 images.

Some optional equipment to consider includes…

  • an external flash unit
  • extension tubes
  • close-up adapter

This Edmonton Macro Photography class includes:

Amanda Scott
BA, Dip. Transpersonal Art Therapy, Dip. Youth Work
Member AAHTC (Australian Association of Holistic and Transpersonal Counselling) Assoc Member ACATA Australian Creative Arts Therapy Association

 
 

Amanda is passionate about living fully, self discovery and connection.

 
Over the past ten years Amanda has worked as a Youth Facilitator, running various self empowerment programs, workshops, camps and seminars. During this time she studied a Bachelor of Art, Visual Art and Photography, Diploma of Youth Work and a Diploma of Transpersonal Art Therapy. 

Amanda now runs workshops and camps as a community facilitator supporting children and young people involved in the child protections system. Amanda aims to use her skills in art therapy and group facilitation to journey with clients into a space that they can connect with their own intuition and inner knowing, to find the tools to fulfil their potential and live a meaningful life.

Amanda specialises in working with children, teenagers and young adults and has worked with themes such as loneliness and isolation, depression and anxiety, grief, loss, trauma and spiritual crises. Amanda believes that the healing is inside us, and offers guidance to find that within ourselves.
My approach begins with developing a safe space for a client to enter into, or continue on, a journey of self-discovery. 

I will journey alongside the client, focussing on strengthening their ego and personality in relating to the world, expanding their perspective, and developing a connection to their spirit and purpose. I will encourage those I work with to explore their unconscious world and significant internal experiences and patterns, bringing light, awareness and healing. 

What is Art Therapy?

Art therapy uses creative processes, including art making, drama, and movement to improve and enhance physical, mental and emotional well-being. Art therapy works by accessing imagination and creativity, to develop a more integrated sense of self, with increased self awareness and acceptance.

Art Therapy can help us to find and create our life story, find meaning, purpose and direction in our life. The process can help us to heal ourselves and others and reach our full potential.

What is Transpersonal Art Therapy?


"Transpersonal work provides people in crises with an alternative to symptom suppression. It helps them to creatively adapt to their crisis, using the experience to grow and truly heal. The experience is transformed into a breakthrough rather than breakdown." 
- Phoenix Institute of Australia

Transpersonal Art Therapy uses a psycho-spiritual approach to counselling, recognises a spectrum of consciousness, including altered states, dreams, intuition and a collective consciousness, and accesses creativity to work through problems and issues.

Transpersonal Art Therapy encourages self awareness which leads to authenticity and personal empowerment, is client centred and based on the Shamanic Model, encourages holistic healing by considering mind, body, spirit and environment.

How can I benefit from Art Therapy?


Some benefits you may experience through the therapeutic journey include:
  • Experiencing a safe and supportive environment to explore aspects you may normally keep hidden
  • Clarifying concerns or challenges
  • Working through and healing personal issues and traumas
  • Developing strategies to better cope with anxiety, depression, fear, grief, or loss.
  • Gaining support through life transitions
  • Self expression when you may not be able to describe how you are feeling with words alone
  • Acceptance of all parts of self and assisting to become whole
  • Renewed understanding of personal meaning and discovery of inner resources
  • Reconnecting with creativity
  • Increasing self esteem, self worth and confidence
  • Developing healthy coping skills
  • Self empowerment, strength and an understanding of personal values when making life decisions.
